  "prompt": "Which is the best book of linear algebra?",
  "response": "The \"best\" book for linear algebra can vary depending on your background and what you're looking to get out of the book. However, several highly regarded textbooks are frequently mentioned:\n\n1. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - This book is praised for its clear explanations and focus on understanding the theory and concepts of linear algebra.\n\n2. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang** - Strang's book is known for its applied approach and is widely used in many undergraduate courses.\n\n3. **\"Linear Algebra\" by Serge Lang** - Lang's text is comprehensive and rigorous, suitable for those with a strong mathematical background.\n\n4. **\"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by David C. Lay, Steven R. Lay, and Judi J. McDonald** - This is a popular textbook for undergraduate courses, known for its practical applications and accessibility.\n\n5. **\"Matrix Analysis and Applied Linear Algebra\" by Carl D. Meyer** - Recommended for those seeking a balance between theory and application, it\u2019s often used in engineering and applied sciences.\n\nEach of these books has its strengths and target audience, so the \"best\" one depends on your personal needs and learning style.",
